{
  "answer": "**In the Nāradasmṛti (also spelled Naradasmriti), the 18 *vyavahāra-padas*—the \"titles\" or \"topics\" of law—are enumerated at the outset of the text in *Mātṛkā* 1 (the first table of contents), which introduces the structure of legal procedure (*vyavahāra*).**[^1]\n\nThese are explicitly listed across four verses (Nar. M1.16–19), as follows:\n\n1. Non-payment of debt (*ṛṇa*)\n2. Deposits (*nikṣepa*)\n3. Partnership (*saṁsṛṣṭi*)\n4. Resumption of a gift (*dānapratigrahaṇa*)\n5. Refusal to render service after agreeing to it (*pratibhu-avahetum*)\n6. Non-payment of wages (*karmakara*)\n7. Sale by one who is not the owner (*asvāmibhūmi*)\n8. Non-delivery of a sold article (*vikrayānapaharaṇa*)\n9. Rescission of a purchase (*krayavikraya*)\n10. Breach of an agreement (*saṁsthā*)\n11. Disputes concerning land (*prthvīvyavahāra*)\n12. The relationship between man and woman (*strīpuṃsaṃgama*)\n13. Inheritance (*dāyabhāga*)\n14. Crimes of violence (*sāhasa*)\n15. Verbal assault (*vākpāruṣya*)\n16. Physical assault (*daṇḍapāruṣya*)\n17. Gambling and betting (*dyūta*)\n18. Miscellaneous matters (*prakīrṇaka*)\n\n**The text frames these as the core \"eighteen topics\" (*aṣṭādaśa-pada*) of litigation within the broader system of law, which has \"eight limbs, eighteen topics, and likewise a hundred branches.\"**[^2]\n\n**Each topic is then elaborated in detail later in the single chapter (sections 1–18), providing rules, procedures, witnesses, ordeals, and penalties specific to that title.**[^3]\n\n[^1]: Nārada, *Nāradasmṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-79e060).\n[^2]: Nārada, *Nāradasmṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-79e060).\n[^3]: Nārada, *Nāradasmṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-99f176).",
